        "body":"<p>Thousands of pensioners who feared their bonds in Co-operative Bank would be near worthless have been offered a new deal in what campaigners have hailed as a victory for small investors.</p><p>An estimated 15,000 holders of Co-op Bank bonds, called Pibs (permanent interest-bearing securities) saw the price plunge from 160p to just 60p and interest payments suspended as financial crisis engulfed the bank this year.</p><p>Initially it was thought the bonds would be swapped for shares in the bank, of uncertain value and with little or no dividends.</p><p>Outraged pensioners, many of whom bought the bonds to provide a secure retirement income – they paid annual interest ranging from 5% to 13% – formed an action group to fight the proposals. They have now been offered an alternative that will still leave them out of pocket, but by much less than originally feared.</p><p>Holders of the 13% bond will be offered a choice of continuing the 13% income a year until 2025, but losing all their underlying capital, or getting 9.2% a year until 2025 and 84% of their capital back.</p><p>A similar deal is on offer to 9.2% preference share holders, while investors getting 5.5% Pibs will be offered a new bond paying 5.8%, but will lose nearly half of their underlying capital.</p><p>Bond expert Mark Taber, who helped form the action group to fight for a better deal, and signed up 2,500 members, said the outcome is the best small investors could have hoped for. \"It's a very different deal to that offered to us in June and shows that Co-operative Bank were really listening to us. This deal has been extremely hard-fought and is now a much better solution for retail holders and pensioners.\"</p><p>Many Pibs were issued at generous interest rates in the 1990s by building societies such as Britannia (later acquired by Co-op Bank) that made them very attractive for pensioners seeking a steady, reliable income in retirement. But they are not protected by the Financial Services Compensation Scheme if a company gets into financial difficulty, and rank lowly behind other creditors when a company crashes.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421648629|2013-11-05T11:03:48Z|918b580dfbdbf1bab08fcf47a0f1f8bbf599b72c -->",
