      "id":"business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/nov/04/co-op-bank-losses",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-04T19:38:39Z",
      "webTitle":"Co-op Bank could have years of losses ahead | Analysis",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/nov/04/co-op-bank-losses",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/nov/04/co-op-bank-losses",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"4",
        "trailText":"When you've got only 275 branches, making serious money outside the big boys' oligopoly is a challenge, says <strong>Nils Pratley</strong>",
        "headline":"Co-op Bank could have years of losses ahead",
        "body":"<p>The popular caricature that the Co-op Bank is being fleeced by a bunch of rapacious US hedge funds is not quite accurate. It is certainly true that the Co-op, having blustered that it needed to retain majority control of the bank, has been forced into a humiliating U-turn. Under the rejigged arrangements to raise capital, the Co-op will emerge with only a 30% stake plus a new \"ethical constitution\" to cover its embarrassment.</p><p>But, as one surveys the financial disaster, another thought occurs: the US funds and their co-travellers in the bank's senior bonds will not enjoy a free lunch. They will own 70% of a bank that is small, loss-making and in need of heavy investment.</p><p>To get a measure of how far the Co-op Bank has fallen, consider this detail in Monday's documents: the colossal sum of £500m will have to be spent \"in connection with the re-engineering of the bank's IT platform\". That is from a bank that has already written off about £300m from past technology misadventures.</p><p>Then there's a closure programme that will see at least 15% of branches shut, plus the continuing burden of bad loans. Add it all up, and the Co-op predicts the bank will be loss-making in 2013 and 2014 and possibly \"for some years thereafter\".</p><p>Why were the US funds so keen to lobby for a greater shareholding, thereby writing off a greater proportion of their bonds? The official answer (or semi-official as the key hedge funds – Silver Point and Aurelius – decline to speak for themselves) is that the bank's recovery could be profitable for owners prepared to be patient.</p><p>Well, yes, if better managers can avoid so many self-inflicted accidents, returns should improve one day. On the other hand, when you've got only 275 branches, making serious money outside the big boys' oligopoly is a challenge. One part of the US funds' thinking may be that shares in a bank listed on the stock market are easier to trade than impaired bonds.</p><p>In day-to-day terms, the hope is that an ethical constitution, policed by a boardroom committee, will keep the Co-op Bank's ethical halo in place and thus encourage loyalty among customers. We'll see. For what it's worth, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/poll/2013/oct/22/co-op-bank-ethical-stance-group-lost-majority-control\" title=\"\">respondents to this newspaper's online poll were sceptical</a>: some 88% thought the ethical stance could not be retained without majority control by the Co-op.</p><p>The only winners, relatively speaking, are retail investors in the junior bonds. Thanks to Mark Taber's campaign on behalf of pensioners and others, they have got substantially better terms than a textbook restructuring would have suggested. The outcome is not painless for the pensioners but income, rather than shares, is what the junior bondholders wanted and the Co-op, asked to live up to its ethical mantra, has been persuaded to cough up £129m. Smart negotiating, Mr Taber.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421650029|2013-11-05T11:03:48Z|d93e34e54d53b6bcc4f8cb8aa607dddd7288aa98 -->",
