      "id":"business/2013/nov/04/co-operative-group-admits-regulators-questioning-financial-strength",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-04T21:51:58Z",
      "webTitle":"Co-op Group admits regulators asking about bank's reported financial strength",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/04/co-operative-group-admits-regulators-questioning-financial-strength",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/nov/04/co-operative-group-admits-regulators-questioning-financial-strength",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Co-operative Bank says City regulator has been questioning information in bank's 2012 annual report and accounts",
        "headline":"Co-op Group admits regulators asking about bank's reported financial strength",
        "body":"<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Co-operative Group disclosed on Monday that regulators have been asking questions about information that its bank provided to investors about its financial strength in 2012.</p><p>In legal warnings made in more than 1,000 pages of documents published alongside the £1.5bn rescue deal for the bank, the group said that the City regulator and accountancy bodies had been asking for details about information contained in the bank's 2012 annual report and accounts.</p><p>The bank had examined the information provided and concluded that the statements made could appear inaccurate if read in isolation from other parts of the report and accounts. But when the statements were read alongside the rest of the report this was not the situation and the bank had concluded that it did not need to reissue its report and accounts.</p><p>The bank said the enquiries by the regulators – the Financial Conduct Authority and the Financial Reporting Council – were at a preliminary stage and that it could not determine if a formal investigation might begin.</p><p>It said the FCA and the conduct committee of the FRC had asked about disclosures about the regulatory capital position as well as details about the loan-impairment provision, the impairment charge of its IT systems and the way it had valued its debt.</p><p>As an example, it provided the formal wording used on page 80 of its 2012 report, which related to the intricate detail of rules set out by the then-regulator, the Financial Services Authority, and its approach to individual rules for each bank.</p><p>On page 80 the Co-op bank had said that \"adequate capitalisation can be maintained at all times even under the most severe stress scenarios, including the revised FSA 'anchor' stress scenario\" and also \"a capital buffer above individual capital guidance (ICG) is being maintained to provide the ability to absorb capital shocks and ensure sufficient surplus capital is available at all times to cover the bank's regulatory minimum requirements\".</p><p>After reviewing the statements, the bank's board had concluded that they were inaccurate if read in isolation  but along with the auditors KPMG, it did not believe the formal report should be reissued.</p><p>\"The board of the bank has reviewed the basis for these statements and has concluded that they are inaccurate and, should they be read in isolation, these statements could be misleading, but when taken in the context of the 2012 accounts as a whole, including the disclosures on pages 18, 29 and 30 of the 2012 accounts, a more balanced view can be formed,\" the group said.</p><p>The Co-op Group, which owns supermarkets, pharmacies and funeral homes, made the disclosures as it published details of a plan to inject £1.5bn into the bank – and under which it would lose 100% ownership of the bank. Bondholders, led by US hedge funds, are to take a 70% stake in the bank.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421655544|2013-11-05T11:03:48Z|3e358171c5ff2f96a29784415cace3d0b075f43a -->",
